/* Teach me from the ground up: FE-CSSARCH (auto-assembled) */
enh({
  "the-cascade": {"teach":"<p>At its core, the cascade is just <strong>the tournament CSS runs whenever two or more rules try to style the same thing on the same element</strong>. Something has to win, and the cascade is the ordered list of tie-breakers the browser walks through to pick that winner.</p><h4>The order of rounds</h4><p>Here is the part almost everyone gets wrong: specificity is <em>not</em> the first round. The browser checks these stages in this exact order, and <strong>the first stage that produces a winner ends the contest</strong>:</p><ul><li><strong>Origin &amp; importance</strong> — who wrote the rule (the browser's user-agent stylesheet, the user, or you the author) combined with whether <code>!important</code> is attached.</li><li><strong>Cascade layers</strong> — which <code>@layer</code> bucket the rule lives in.</li><li><strong>Specificity</strong> — how targeted the selector is.</li><li><strong>Source order</strong> — which rule appears later in the source.</li></ul><div class=\"analogy\">Think of it like a courthouse appeals system. Before a judge ever weighs how detailed your argument is (specificity), the system first asks which court the ruling came from (origin), and whether someone invoked a special override (<code>!important</code>). A scribbled one-line ruling from a higher court still beats a 50-page brief from a lower one. Only inside the <em>same</em> court does the detail of the argument decide things.</div><h4>The !important twist</h4><p>Normally author styles beat user styles beat browser defaults. But <code>!important</code> <strong>reverses the origin order</strong>. So a browser's <code>!important</code> rule outranks your author <code>!important</code> rule — a deliberate accessibility escape hatch so users can force, say, large text that no website can override.</p><h4>Why layers change the game</h4><p>Because layers are sorted <em>before</em> specificity, a plain low-specificity rule in a later layer beats a high-specificity rule in an earlier layer. This is precisely why <code>@layer</code> lets you retire the old arms race of piling on IDs and <code>!important</code> just to win.</p><h4>Animations and transitions</h4><p>Two special citizens sit outside the normal pecking order. A running CSS <strong>animation</strong> overrides normal declarations but still loses to <code>!important</code>. A running <strong>transition</strong> overrides <em>everything</em>, even <code>!important</code> — because while it is mid-flight, its value is the live truth on screen.</p><p>Worked through: author <code>!important</code> beats author normal; a browser <code>!important</code> beats your author <code>!important</code> (importance flips origins); and a transition beats even a browser <code>!important</code>.</p><div class=\"key\">The cascade resolves conflicts in stages — origin/importance, then layers, then specificity, then source order — and the <em>first</em> stage to break the tie wins. Specificity only matters once everything above it is equal.</div>"},
  "specificity": {"teach":"<p>At its core, specificity is just <strong>a score the browser gives each selector to measure how narrowly it targets an element</strong> — and it uses that score to break ties when two rules in the same layer and origin both want to style the same thing.</p><h4>The three-column score</h4><p>The score is a tuple of three numbers, often written <code>(a, b, c)</code>:</p><ul><li><strong>a</strong> = number of <strong>ID</strong> selectors (<code>#nav</code>)</li><li><strong>b</strong> = number of <strong>classes, attribute selectors, and pseudo-classes</strong> (<code>.link</code>, <code>[type=text]</code>, <code>:hover</code>)</li><li><strong>c</strong> = number of <strong>type selectors and pseudo-elements</strong> (<code>div</code>, <code>::before</code>)</li></ul><p>You compare two scores <strong>left to right</strong>, column by column. The crucial rule: <strong>columns never overflow into each other</strong>. The first column where they differ decides the winner, full stop — no matter how lopsided the later columns are.</p><div class=\"analogy\">Treat it like comparing version numbers, not regular numbers. Version <code>1.0.0</code> beats <code>0.99.99</code> — the leading <code>1</code> wins and nothing in the later slots can claw it back. It is decidedly <em>not</em> base-10: eleven classes do not 'carry' into an ID. <code>(0,11,0)</code> still loses to <code>(1,0,0)</code> because the ID column is checked first and it is a clean 1-vs-0.</div><h4>The special cases</h4><ul><li><code>*</code> (universal) and combinators (<code>&gt;</code>, <code>+</code>, <code>~</code>, space) add <strong>zero</strong>.</li><li><code>:where()</code> forces its contents to <strong>(0,0,0)</strong> — a deliberate zero.</li><li><code>:is()</code>, <code>:not()</code>, and <code>:has()</code> take the specificity of their <strong>most specific argument</strong>.</li><li><strong>Inline styles</strong> (<code>style=\"...\"</code>) outrank any selector.</li><li><code>!important</code> is not part of this tuple at all — it lives in a separate cascade dimension entirely.</li></ul><h4>Why this matters in practice</h4><p>Misreading specificity as base-10 leads to real bugs: people assume stacking enough classes will eventually beat an ID, then waste an afternoon when it never does. Understanding the column model tells you the only ways to out-rank an ID are another ID, inline styles, <code>!important</code>, a higher cascade layer, or simply not fighting it.</p><p>Worked example: <code>#nav .link</code> scores <code>(1,1,0)</code>. The far longer <code>.header .nav ul li a.link</code> scores <code>(0,2,4)</code>. The first one wins — the contest is decided in the very first column, <code>1</code> versus <code>0</code>, and the four type selectors in the loser are irrelevant.</p><div class=\"key\">Specificity is a three-column tuple <code>(IDs, classes, types)</code> compared independently left-to-right with no carrying — so one ID beats any number of classes, and your instinct to read it as a single base-10 number is the trap.</div>"},
  "cascade-layers": {"teach":"<p>At its core, a cascade layer is just <strong>a named priority bucket you drop styles into, and the bucket's rank decides the winner before specificity is even consulted</strong>. It is a way to say 'these styles should always be able to override those styles' without ever touching selector strength.</p><h4>Declaring the order</h4><p>You name your layers up front, and that line fixes their precedence:</p><ul><li><code>@layer reset, base, components, utilities;</code></li></ul><p>For normal (non-<code>!important</code>) declarations, <strong>later-declared layers win</strong>. So <code>utilities</code> beats <code>components</code> beats <code>base</code> beats <code>reset</code> — regardless of how specific the selectors inside each are. A bare <code>a {}</code> in <code>utilities</code> beats a <code>#sidebar .nav a {}</code> in <code>base</code>.</p><div class=\"analogy\">Picture printing on transparency sheets and stacking them on an overhead projector. The order you stack the sheets decides what shows through — a faint pencil mark on the top sheet hides a bold marker stroke on a sheet below it. Specificity is how dark your mark is; layer order is which sheet sits on top. Stacking order wins.</div><h4>Why it tames third-party CSS</h4><p>Import a vendor stylesheet straight into a low layer — <code>@import url(framework.css) layer(vendor)</code> — and now <em>any</em> rule in a later layer overrides it effortlessly. This is how teams retire the old <code>!important</code> wars: you no longer escalate specificity to win, you just put your styles in a higher-ranked layer.</p><h4>The two twists that trip people up</h4><ul><li><strong>Unlayered normal styles beat all layered ones.</strong> Anything you write outside any <code>@layer</code> sits <em>above</em> every layer for normal declarations. So a stray un-layered rule can quietly override your whole 'utilities' layer.</li><li><strong>For <code>!important</code>, the entire layer order reverses.</strong> The layer you declared <em>first</em> now wins. And important <em>unlayered</em> styles drop <em>below</em> important <em>layered</em> ones — the mirror image of the normal case.</li></ul><h4>Worked example</h4><p>Given <code>@layer base { a { color: red !important } }</code> then <code>@layer theme { a { color: blue !important } }</code>, the result is <strong>red</strong>. With <code>!important</code> the layer order flips, so the earlier-declared <code>base</code> layer wins even though <code>theme</code> came later.</p><div class=\"key\">Layers are precedence bands checked <em>before</em> specificity: later layers win for normal styles, but two gotchas bite — unlayered normal styles outrank everything layered, and <code>!important</code> reverses the whole layer order.</div>"},
  "custom-properties": {"teach":"<p>At its core, a custom property is just <strong>a real, live variable that lives inside the page itself — you can set it, read it from another rule, inherit it down the tree, and change it on the fly</strong>. Unlike the variables in Sass or Less, it does not vanish when the build finishes; it is part of the running document.</p><h4>The syntax</h4><ul><li>You define one with a double-dash name: <code>--gap: 1rem;</code></li><li>You read it with the <code>var()</code> function: <code>gap: var(--gap, 0)</code>, where <code>0</code> is a fallback used only if <code>--gap</code> is unset.</li></ul><h4>The key behaviors</h4><p>Three properties make them powerful:</p><ul><li><strong>They cascade and inherit.</strong> Set <code>--gap</code> on <code>:root</code> and every descendant can read it. Override it on a child and that subtree sees the new value — this is how scoped theming works without rewriting any rule.</li><li><strong>They are scriptable.</strong> JavaScript can do <code>element.style.setProperty('--gap', '2rem')</code> at runtime, so design tokens become reactive.</li><li><strong>They resolve at computed-value time.</strong> The <code>var()</code> is substituted late in the styling pipeline, which is why they respond to <code>:hover</code>, media queries, and container queries.</li></ul><div class=\"analogy\">Preprocessor variables (<code>$x</code>) are like ingredients written into a recipe: once the cake is baked, the word 'sugar' is gone — only the baked-in result remains. Custom properties are like labeled dials on the oven that stay on the appliance after baking. You can turn the 'temperature' dial mid-bake, and the cake responds. That live, adjustable quality is the whole point.</div><h4>Why it matters</h4><p>Because they are live and inheriting, a single token like <code>--brand</code> on <code>:root</code> can re-theme an entire app — flip it in a <code>prefers-color-scheme: dark</code> block and every component recolors with zero extra selectors. Registering a property with <code>@property</code> goes further: you can declare a syntax type, an initial value, and whether it inherits, so invalid values degrade cleanly and the value can even animate smoothly.</p><h4>The gotcha to internalize</h4><p>The <code>var()</code> fallback is <em>not</em> a type-checker. It fires only when the variable is <strong>unset</strong>. If <code>--x</code> exists but holds a value that is invalid for the property you used it in, the fallback is ignored entirely and you hit invalid-at-computed-value-time instead.</p><h4>Worked example</h4><p><code>:root { --gap: 1rem }</code> then <code>.tight { --gap: .25rem }</code> then <code>.box { gap: var(--gap, 0) }</code>. A <code>.box</code> inside <code>.tight</code> inherits the smaller <code>.25rem</code> — the scope override flows down by inheritance, no new rule on <code>.box</code> needed.</p><div class=\"key\">Custom properties are live, inheriting, scriptable values resolved at computed-value time — that runtime nature is what makes theming and scoped overrides possible, and is exactly what preprocessor variables can never do.</div>"},
  "var-fallback": {"teach":"<p>At its core, the second argument to <code>var()</code> is just <strong>a backup value used when the variable simply isn't there</strong> — and the most important thing to learn is everything it is <em>not</em>. It is not a validator, not a type guard, and not a safety net against bad values.</p><h4>When the fallback actually fires</h4><p>In <code>var(--x, default)</code>, the <code>default</code> is used in exactly one situation: when <code>--x</code> is <strong>missing</strong> (never set) or holds the special 'guaranteed-invalid value'. If the variable exists at all and resolves to <em>some</em> value, the fallback is completely ignored — even if that value makes no sense for the property.</p><h4>Invalid at computed-value time (IACVT)</h4><p>Here is the trap. Suppose <code>--w</code> is set to <code>red</code>, and you write <code>width: var(--w, 10px)</code>. The variable <em>is</em> set, so the fallback never enters the picture. The browser substitutes <code>red</code> into <code>width</code>, discovers <code>width: red</code> is nonsense, and declares the whole declaration <strong>invalid at computed-value time</strong>.</p><p>IACVT does <em>not</em> mean 'use the fallback' and it does <em>not</em> mean 'use the previous cascaded value'. It means the property resolves to:</p><ul><li>its <strong>inherited</strong> value, if the property is an inheriting one, or</li><li>its <strong>initial</strong> value, if it is not.</li></ul><p>Since <code>width</code> is non-inherited, it falls back to its initial value <code>auto</code> — not your <code>10px</code>.</p><div class=\"analogy\">Think of the fallback as a spare tire that only deploys if there is <em>no tire on the rim at all</em>. If there is a tire but it is the wrong size — a bicycle tire on a truck — the car does not reach for the spare; it just refuses to drive and rolls back to the factory default ride height (initial/inherited). The spare can't help with a wrong-but-present tire.</div><h4>How to actually get a safety net</h4><p>Register the property with <code>@property</code>. By giving it a <code>syntax</code> type and an <code>initial-value</code>, a bad resolved value falls back to that declared initial value instead of triggering IACVT — and, as a bonus, the property becomes animatable because the browser now understands its type.</p><h4>Worked example</h4><p><code>.x { --w: red; width: var(--w, 10px) }</code> → <code>--w</code> is set, so <code>10px</code> is never used → <code>width: red</code> is invalid → IACVT → <code>width</code> resolves to its initial value <strong><code>auto</code></strong>, decidedly not <code>10px</code>.</p><div class=\"key\">The <code>var()</code> fallback only covers a <em>missing</em> variable, not a defined-but-invalid one; a bad resolved value triggers IACVT and lands on the property's inherited/initial value. Only <code>@property</code>'s <code>initial-value</code> gives you true type-safety.</div>"},
  "container-queries": {"teach":"<p>At its core, a container query lets <strong>a component style itself based on how much room it was given, instead of how big the whole browser window is</strong>. It is the difference between 'when the screen is wide' and 'when <em>my slot</em> is wide' — and that distinction is what finally makes components truly reusable.</p><h4>Setting up a container</h4><p>You opt an ancestor in as a queryable container:</p><ul><li><code>container-type: inline-size</code> — the container can be queried on its inline (usually horizontal) dimension.</li><li><code>container-type: size</code> — queryable on both dimensions (requires the container have an explicit size).</li></ul><p>Then descendants react with <code>@container (min-width: 30rem) { … }</code>, which asks 'is my nearest query container at least 30rem wide?'</p><div class=\"analogy\">A media query is like dressing for the <em>weather of the whole city</em> — one forecast for everyone, no matter which room you're standing in. A container query is like dressing for the <em>temperature of the actual room you walked into</em>. Drop the same card component into a narrow sidebar and it wears its compact outfit; drop it into a wide main grid and it stretches out — each instance reads its own room, not the city forecast.</div><h4>Container query units</h4><p>You also get units that resolve against the nearest matching container rather than the viewport: <code>cqw</code>, <code>cqh</code>, <code>cqi</code> (inline), <code>cqb</code> (block), and <code>cqmin</code>/<code>cqmax</code>. So <code>font-size: 5cqi</code> scales with the container's inline size — fluid typography that ignores the window entirely.</p><h4>The ancestor-only rule</h4><p>You can only query an <strong>ancestor</strong> container, <em>never the element's own box</em>. This is a hard constraint, not a quirk: an element styling itself based on its own size would create a circular dependency (the style changes the size, which changes the query, which changes the style...). So you mark a wrapper as the container and query it from inside.</p><h4>The gotcha that bites</h4><p>Setting <code>container-type: inline-size</code> turns on <strong>inline-size containment</strong>. That can <em>collapse</em> a container's width if it was previously sized by its content. An element that used to be 'as wide as its text' may suddenly shrink, because containment tells the browser to stop sizing it from its children. The fix is usually to give the container an explicit width or let a parent layout (grid/flex) determine it.</p><h4>Worked example</h4><p><code>.sidebar { container-type: inline-size }</code> then inside it <code>.card { display: grid }</code> and <code>@container (min-width: 400px) { .card { grid-template-columns: 1fr 2fr } }</code>. The card stays single-column in a narrow sidebar and becomes a two-column layout only when its container crosses 400px — no matter what the viewport is doing.</p><div class=\"key\">Container queries let components respond to their context's size via an <em>ancestor</em> container — never their own box — which is what makes one component layout correctly in a sidebar and a wide grid alike; just watch for inline-size containment collapsing the container's width.</div>"},
  "media-queries": {"teach":"<p>At its core, a media query is just <strong>a gate that says 'only apply these styles when some condition about the screen or the user is true.'</strong> That condition might be a viewport width, or a user preference like dark mode or reduced motion.</p><h4>What you can gate on</h4><ul><li><strong>Viewport dimensions:</strong> <code>@media (width &gt;= 48rem) { … }</code></li><li><strong>User preferences:</strong> <code>prefers-color-scheme: dark</code>, <code>prefers-reduced-motion: reduce</code> — these read accessibility and theming settings from the operating system.</li></ul><h4>Mobile-first, and why it's the default discipline</h4><p>Mobile-first means you write your <strong>base styles for the smallest screen</strong>, then layer enhancements upward using <code>min-width</code> queries. The small-screen layout is the unconditional default; bigger screens opt into more.</p><div class=\"analogy\">Think of packing a travel bag. Mobile-first is starting with the absolute essentials that you carry everywhere (the base styles), then <em>adding</em> a coat when you know it'll be cold (a <code>min-width</code> enhancement). The opposite — desktop-first — is like packing for a blizzard and then frantically <em>removing</em> things at each warmer destination. Adding as conditions allow is cleaner, lighter, and cascades naturally; the smallest device downloads the leanest set of rules and never has to undo desktop assumptions.</div><h4>Modern range syntax</h4><p>You can now write real comparisons: <code>@media (width &gt;= 48rem)</code> and <code>@media (480px &lt;= width &lt; 768px)</code>. This replaces the old <code>min-width</code>/<code>max-width</code> pairs and, importantly, kills the notorious <code>0.02px</code> overlap workaround people used to avoid two breakpoints both firing at the exact boundary pixel.</p><h4>Use rem breakpoints</h4><p>Prefer <code>rem</code> over <code>px</code> for breakpoints. Because <code>rem</code> scales with the user's root font size, a person who bumps their default text size gets breakpoints that move with them — the layout reflows to suit their actual reading size rather than a fixed pixel count.</p><h4>The gotcha</h4><p>If you mix old-style <code>min-width</code> and <code>max-width</code> with the <em>same boundary value</em> (e.g. both <code>max-width: 768px</code> and <code>min-width: 768px</code>), at exactly <code>768px</code> <strong>both</strong> queries match and you get double-styling — the classic reason the 0.02px hack existed. Range syntax with <code>&lt;</code> versus <code>&gt;=</code> sidesteps it cleanly.</p><h4>Worked example</h4><p><code>.grid { grid-template-columns: 1fr }</code> as the mobile base, then <code>@media (width &gt;= 48rem) { .grid { grid-template-columns: repeat(3, 1fr) } }</code> — one column by default, three columns only once the viewport reaches 48rem.</p><div class=\"key\">Write smallest-screen styles as your unconditional base and enhance upward with <code>min-width</code> / range queries in <code>rem</code> — it ships the lightest defaults, cascades cleanly, and the modern range syntax retires the min-/max- overlap bug for good.</div>"},
  "logical-properties": {"teach":"<p>At its core, a logical property is just <strong>spacing or sizing that's described by the flow of the text rather than by fixed physical sides like 'left' and 'right.'</strong> You say 'put space where the text starts,' and the browser figures out whether that's the left edge, the right edge, or the top, depending on the writing mode.</p><h4>Two axes: inline and block</h4><p>Logical properties think in two flow-relative directions:</p><ul><li><strong>Inline</strong> = the direction text runs. In English (LTR) that's left-to-right; in Arabic/Hebrew (RTL) it's right-to-left; in vertical Japanese it runs top-to-bottom.</li><li><strong>Block</strong> = the direction lines stack. In English that's top-to-bottom.</li></ul><p>So <code>margin-inline-start</code> is 'margin where the text begins,' <code>padding-block</code> is 'padding along the line-stacking axis (top and bottom in English),' <code>inset-inline-end</code> is the offset at the 'end' edge, and <code>inline-size</code> is the size along the text direction (width in English).</p><div class=\"analogy\">Physical properties are like giving directions as 'turn north, then east' — correct only if everyone faces the same way you do. Logical properties are like saying 'turn toward where you're heading, then to your right.' Hand those instructions to someone walking the opposite direction and they still work, because the directions are relative to <em>their</em> orientation, not a fixed compass. That's exactly how <code>margin-inline-start</code> stays correct whether the reader's text flows left-to-right or right-to-left.</div><h4>Why this matters: internationalization</h4><p>The payoff is enormous for multilingual UIs. With physical properties, an icon nudged with <code>margin-left: .5rem</code> sits to the right of its label in English — but in Arabic the whole layout mirrors, the label is now on the other side, and your left margin is suddenly in the wrong place. Teams used to fix this with entire <code>[dir=rtl]</code> override stylesheets that re-declared every directional property.</p><p>Logical properties delete that whole category of work. A single <code>margin-inline-end: .5rem</code> is automatically correct in LTR (space on the right), RTL (space on the left), and vertical writing modes — because it always means 'at the end of the text flow,' and the browser reorients it for you.</p><h4>The gotcha</h4><p>The trap is hard-coding <code>margin-left</code>/<code>margin-right</code> on directional UI like icons, badges, and chevrons, then shipping to an Arabic or Hebrew locale and watching the spacing land on the wrong side. The mirroring breaks because physical sides don't follow the flipped text direction.</p><h4>Worked example</h4><p><code>.icon { margin-inline-end: .5rem }</code> — the icon gets trailing space on its right in LTR, and that same rule automatically puts the space on its left in RTL, with no override stylesheet at all.</p><div class=\"key\">Logical properties map to the text's flow (inline = text direction, block = line stacking) instead of physical sides, so one declaration is correct in LTR, RTL, and vertical writing modes — making them essential for internationalized UIs and the cure for <code>[dir=rtl]</code> override sheets.</div>"},
  "is-where": {"teach":"<p>At its core, <code>:is()</code> and <code>:where()</code> are just <strong>two ways to group several selectors into one, so you write less repetitive CSS</strong> — and the one real difference between them is what they do to specificity.</p><h4>What they share</h4><p>Both take a <em>selector list</em> and match an element if it matches any selector in the list. So <code>:is(h1, h2, h3)</code> is a compact way of saying 'an h1 or h2 or h3.' Both are also <strong>forgiving</strong>: if you include a selector the browser doesn't understand, that one entry is silently dropped and the rest of the list still works — instead of the whole rule being thrown out.</p><h4>The one difference: specificity</h4><ul><li><code>:is()</code> contributes the specificity of its <strong>most specific argument</strong>. So <code>:is(#id, .x)</code> inherits the ID's weight, <code>(1,0,0)</code>.</li><li><code>:where()</code> always contributes <strong>(0,0,0)</strong>, no matter what's inside it. It's a deliberate specificity eraser.</li></ul><div class=\"analogy\">Imagine two highlighters that both let you mark several names on a guest list at once. The <code>:is()</code> highlighter inks each name with the boldness of the boldest VIP in the group — so the whole group is now hard to overwrite. The <code>:where()</code> highlighter uses invisible ink for weight: it marks the names but adds zero boldness, so anyone can scribble over them later. Same grouping power, opposite consequences for who wins the next edit.</div><h4>When to reach for each</h4><p>Use <code>:where()</code> for <strong>design-system base styles</strong> you want to be trivially overridable: <code>:where(h1, h2, h3) { margin: 0 }</code> sets a sane default that any later rule beats without a fight, because it added zero specificity. Use <code>:is()</code> when you want terse grouping but still expect the rule to carry normal weight in the cascade.</p><h4>The connection to nesting</h4><p>Native CSS nesting matters here: when you nest, the browser wraps the substituted parent selector in an implicit <code>:is()</code>. That's why nesting can quietly <em>raise</em> specificity — the parent's most specific form gets baked in via <code>:is()</code> semantics. If you want nested rules to stay low-weight, you sometimes wrap parts in <code>:where()</code> on purpose.</p><h4>The gotcha</h4><p>People write <code>:is(#id, .x)</code> expecting some kind of average or the <em>lowest</em> weight, then are surprised the rule carries the ID's full <code>(1,0,0)</code>. Remember: <code>:is()</code> takes the <em>most</em> specific argument, not an average and not the least.</p><h4>Worked example</h4><p><code>:where(h1, h2, h3) { margin: 0 }</code> resets heading margins and is easily overridden by any later, even low-specificity, rule — precisely because <code>:where()</code> added zero specificity.</p><div class=\"key\">Both group selectors forgivingly; the difference is weight — <code>:is()</code> takes its most specific argument's specificity, while <code>:where()</code> always contributes zero, making <code>:where()</code> the right tool for easily-overridable design-system defaults.</div>"},
  "has-selector": {"teach":"<p>At its core, <code>:has()</code> is the long-awaited <strong>'parent selector'</strong>: it lets an element style itself based on <em>what it contains</em> or <em>what follows it</em>. For the first time in pure CSS, a parent can react to its children, and an element can react to its siblings.</p><h4>How it reads</h4><p>You attach <code>:has(...)</code> to an element, and the part inside describes a relationship that must hold:</p><ul><li><code>.card:has(img)</code> — a card that contains an image anywhere inside it.</li><li><code>form:has(:invalid)</code> — a form that contains any invalid field (style the whole form red without JavaScript).</li><li><code>h2:has(+ p)</code> — an h2 that is immediately followed by a paragraph (a sibling relationship, not a child one).</li></ul><div class=\"analogy\">Before <code>:has()</code>, CSS could only ever look <em>downward and outward</em> — a parent's styles flowed to children, but a parent was blind to what was inside it, like a sealed gift box that can't tell what's been packed into it. <code>:has()</code> is x-ray vision for that box: the box can now look inside (and even glance at the box sitting next to it) and change its own wrapping accordingly. That's why it's been called the holy grail selector — it inverts the one-way street CSS lived on for decades.</div><h4>Why it's a big deal</h4><p>Whole patterns that used to require JavaScript — 'highlight a label when its checkbox is checked,' 'add a badge to articles that have a video,' 'collapse a layout when a slot is empty' — collapse into a single CSS rule. It's both <strong>state-driven</strong> (reacting to <code>:checked</code>, <code>:invalid</code>) and <strong>structure-driven</strong> (reacting to which children exist).</p><h4>Specificity</h4><p>Its specificity follows the <code>:is()</code> rule: <code>:has()</code> takes the weight of its <strong>most specific argument</strong>, not zero. So <code>.card:has(#hero)</code> picks up the ID's <code>(1,0,0)</code> from inside the parentheses.</p><h4>The gotcha</h4><p>Two traps. First, don't think of it as merely a child check — it's a <em>full relational query</em> that can reach deep descendants and following siblings, so it's far more powerful (and worth scoping with combinators like <code>&gt;</code> or <code>+</code>). Second, unlike <code>:is()</code> and <code>:where()</code>, the argument list inside <code>:has()</code> is <strong>not forgiving</strong> — a single unsupported selector invalidates the entire <code>:has()</code>, so a typo can silently kill the rule.</p><h4>Worked example</h4><p><code>.gallery:has(&gt; :nth-child(4)) { gap: 2rem }</code> — the gallery widens its gap only when it has a fourth direct child (i.e. four or more items). With three items the rule doesn't apply; structure alone drives the styling.</p><div class=\"key\"><code>:has()</code> is CSS's relational 'parent/sibling' selector — it styles an element based on its descendants or following siblings, takes its most specific argument's specificity, and (unlike <code>:is()</code>/<code>:where()</code>) is non-forgiving, so one bad argument breaks the whole selector.</div>"},
  "not-selector": {"teach":"<p>At its core, <code>:not()</code> is just <strong>negation — it matches elements that do <em>not</em> match what's inside it</strong>. The two things that surprise people are that it carries real specificity weight, and that its list form means 'not <em>any</em> of these,' not 'not <em>all</em> of these.'</p><h4>It is not specificity-free</h4><p>You might expect a negation to add nothing, but <code>:not()</code> contributes the specificity of its <strong>most specific argument</strong> — exactly like <code>:is()</code> and <code>:has()</code>. So:</p><ul><li><code>:not(.foo)</code> adds <code>(0,1,0)</code> — the weight of a class.</li><li><code>:not(#id)</code> adds a full <code>(1,0,0)</code> — the weight of an ID.</li></ul><p>That last one is a sneaky source of accidentally-heavy selectors: you write <code>a:not(#main)</code> thinking it's a light tweak and quietly hand it ID-level specificity.</p><h4>The list form distributes</h4><p>The modern <code>:not(.a, .b)</code> is exactly equivalent to <code>:not(.a):not(.b)</code> — negation <strong>distributes</strong> across the list. Read in plain English, it excludes any element matching <code>.a</code> <em>or</em> <code>.b</code>. It does <em>not</em> mean 'not both.'</p><div class=\"analogy\">Think of a bouncer with a list of banned names. <code>:not(.a, .b)</code> is a bouncer who turns away anyone named on the list — match <em>either</em> name and you're out. People misread it as 'only turn away people who are <em>both</em> on the list at once,' which would let almost everyone in. The bouncer excludes on <em>any</em> match, not on a simultaneous match — that's the 'not either, not not-both' distinction.</div><h4>The forgiving twist</h4><p>The list form of <code>:not()</code> is <strong>forgiving</strong>: an unsupported selector in the list is dropped rather than invalidating the whole thing. (Contrast this with <code>:has()</code>, which is <em>not</em> forgiving.)</p><h4>Negating without adding weight</h4><p>If you want the exclusion but none of the specificity baggage, wrap it: <code>:where(:not(.x))</code>. Because <code>:where()</code> forces its contents to <code>(0,0,0)</code>, the negation still filters but adds zero weight — handy for overridable base styles.</p><h4>The gotcha, restated</h4><p>Two traps to avoid: assuming <code>:not()</code> adds zero specificity (it adds its heaviest argument's), and reading <code>:not(.a, .b)</code> as 'not both' when it means 'not either.'</p><h4>Worked example</h4><p><code>li:not(.active, .disabled) { color: gray }</code> targets every <code>li</code> that is <em>neither</em> active <em>nor</em> disabled — equivalent to <code>li:not(.active):not(.disabled)</code>. An item with just one of those classes is already excluded.</p><div class=\"key\"><code>:not()</code> carries the specificity of its most specific argument (so <code>:not(#id)</code> is heavy), and its list form distributes to mean 'not <em>any</em> listed selector' — wrap it in <code>:where()</code> when you want the negation without the weight.</div>"},
  "compositor-props": {"teach":"<p>At its core, this is about <strong>which CSS properties you can animate without forcing the browser to redo expensive work every frame</strong>. A tiny set — <code>transform</code>, <code>opacity</code>, and <code>filter</code> — can animate cheaply on a separate thread, which is why they stay buttery smooth.</p><h4>The rendering pipeline</h4><p>Every frame, the browser can go through up to three stages:</p><ul><li><strong>Layout</strong> — calculate where every box sits and how big it is.</li><li><strong>Paint</strong> — fill in pixels: colors, text, shadows, borders.</li><li><strong>Composite</strong> — assemble the painted layers onto the screen, applying transforms and opacity.</li></ul><p>The first two are the heavy, main-thread stages. The third can run on a separate <strong>compositor thread</strong>.</p><h4>Why transform/opacity/filter are special</h4><p>Animating <code>transform</code>, <code>opacity</code>, or <code>filter</code> only changes how an <em>already-painted</em> layer is assembled. The browser doesn't need to recompute layout or repaint pixels — it just composites the existing layer differently. That work happens on the compositor thread, so even if your JavaScript is busy hammering the main thread, the animation keeps gliding at ~60fps.</p><div class=\"analogy\">Imagine a paper cut-out puppet show. <code>transform</code> and <code>opacity</code> are like sliding a finished cut-out across the stage or fading the stage lights on it — the puppet is already drawn, you're just moving or dimming it. Animating <code>width</code> or <code>left</code> is like <em>redrawing the entire scene with scissors and glue on every single frame</em>: you re-measure where everything goes (layout) and re-color it (paint) sixty times a second. One is effortless; the other guarantees the show stutters.</div><h4>The properties that cause jank</h4><p>Animating geometric or paint properties forces the heavy stages every frame:</p><ul><li><code>width</code>, <code>height</code>, <code>top</code>, <code>left</code>, <code>margin</code> → trigger <strong>layout</strong> (the most expensive), then paint, then composite.</li><li><code>box-shadow</code>, <code>background-color</code>, <code>color</code> → trigger <strong>paint</strong>, then composite.</li></ul><h4>The fixes</h4><ul><li>To <strong>move</strong> something, use <code>transform: translateX(100px)</code> instead of animating <code>left</code>.</li><li>To <strong>fade</strong> something, use <code>opacity</code> instead of toggling <code>visibility</code> or animating <code>color</code>.</li><li>To <strong>resize</strong>, prefer <code>transform: scale()</code> over animating <code>width</code>/<code>height</code>.</li></ul><h4>Worked example</h4><p>Janky: <code>@keyframes a { to { left: 100px } }</code> re-runs layout on every frame. Smooth: <code>@keyframes b { to { transform: translateX(100px) } }</code> stays on the compositor and never touches layout or paint.</p><div class=\"key\">Animate only <code>transform</code>, <code>opacity</code>, and <code>filter</code> for smooth motion — they run on the compositor thread and skip layout and paint, whereas animating <code>left</code>/<code>top</code>/<code>width</code> re-runs the expensive pipeline stages every frame and causes jank.</div>"},
  "will-change": {"teach":"<p>At its core, <code>will-change</code> is just <strong>you telling the browser in advance, 'I'm about to animate this — go get ready.'</strong> The browser responds by promoting the element to its own compositor layer ahead of time, so the very first frame of the animation isn't stalled while that layer is being set up.</p><h4>The problem it solves</h4><p>When an animation starts, the browser may need to create a new GPU layer for the element on the fly. Doing that <em>at the moment the animation begins</em> costs a beat — you can get a tiny hitch on the first frame. <code>will-change: transform</code> moves that preparation earlier, so by the time the animation runs, the layer already exists and the motion is smooth from frame one.</p><div class=\"analogy\">It's like telling a stagehand 'the actor is about to walk on from stage left' before the scene starts. The stagehand positions the spotlight and clears the path in advance, so the entrance is seamless. But if you point the spotlight at <em>every</em> actor backstage 'just in case,' you run the lighting rig out of power and the whole production dims. The hint only helps when used sparingly and pointed at the thing that's actually about to move.</div><h4>Why overusing it backfires</h4><p>Each promoted layer consumes <strong>GPU memory</strong>. Sprinkle <code>will-change</code> across hundreds of elements and you don't speed things up — you exhaust memory, and the browser may start performing <em>worse</em> than if you'd never used it. It is a surgical hint, not a global performance switch.</p><h4>The side effects to know</h4><p>Promotion isn't free of consequences beyond memory. An element with <code>will-change</code> (when it implies a transform-like promotion):</p><ul><li>creates a new <strong>stacking context</strong>, which can change how <code>z-index</code> layering resolves around it.</li><li>becomes a <strong>containing block</strong> for <code>position: fixed</code> descendants — so a fixed child may suddenly anchor to this element instead of the viewport.</li></ul><h4>Best practice</h4><p>Apply it <strong>just before</strong> the animation and <strong>remove it when done</strong>. A common pattern is to add it on <code>:hover</code> (the moment right before the user-triggered animation), or to set it via JavaScript when an animation is about to start and clear it on the transition/animation-end event.</p><h4>Worked example</h4><p><code>.btn:hover { will-change: transform }</code> primes the button the instant the cursor arrives — right before the hover transition fires — and a script can strip the hint once the transition ends so the layer is released and memory is reclaimed.</p><div class=\"key\"><code>will-change</code> is a targeted, temporary hint that promotes an element to its own layer just before animating to avoid first-frame stalls — but each layer costs GPU memory and creates a stacking context and fixed-positioning containing block, so apply it surgically and remove it when the animation ends.</div>"},
  "css-in-js-runtime": {"teach":"<p>At its core, runtime CSS-in-JS is just <strong>writing your styles as JavaScript and having the browser build and inject those styles <em>while the page is rendering</em></strong>. That 'while rendering' part is the whole story — it's convenient to author, but it shifts real work into the render path.</p><h4>What 'runtime' actually means</h4><p>Libraries like styled-components and Emotion let you colocate styles with components and use props in them. To make that work, at render time they:</p><ul><li>serialize your style objects/template literals into CSS strings,</li><li>generate unique class names,</li><li>and inject <code>&lt;style&gt;</code> tags into the document.</li></ul><p>All of this happens <em>every render</em>, on the client, as the user waits — adding per-render CPU cost, extra bundle weight for the style engine itself, and hydration complexity (the server-rendered markup and client runtime must agree on class names).</p><div class=\"analogy\">Runtime CSS-in-JS is like a restaurant that mills its own flour and presses its own oil <em>after</em> you've ordered, every single time a dish goes out. Wonderfully fresh and flexible, but every plate is slower because the prep happens during service. Zero-runtime CSS is the kitchen that does all that milling and pressing the night before (at build time): when the order comes in, the ingredients are ready and the dish leaves the pass instantly.</div><h4>The React Server Components clash</h4><p>There's a sharper, modern problem. React Server Components render <strong>on the server with no client-side JavaScript runtime</strong> — their whole point is to ship less JS. Runtime CSS-in-JS depends on that client runtime to inject styles, so it simply <strong>doesn't run inside Server Components</strong>. Pick styled-components for a Next.js App Router project and you hit this wall directly, on top of the render-time overhead.</p><h4>The 2026 direction: zero-runtime</h4><p>The field has moved toward extracting CSS to a static <code>.css</code> file <em>at build time</em>, so no style engine ships to the browser:</p><ul><li><strong>CSS Modules</strong> — scoped class names resolved at build.</li><li><strong>Tailwind</strong> — utility classes, now with the Oxide engine and Lightning CSS for fast builds.</li><li><strong>Compile-time CSS-in-JS</strong> — vanilla-extract, Panda, Linaria — you still author styles in TypeScript with typing and colocation, but a build step extracts them to static CSS.</li></ul><p>The win is keeping the developer-experience benefits (colocation, type safety) while moving the cost <strong>out of the render path</strong> entirely.</p><h4>Worked example</h4><p>With vanilla-extract, you write styles in a <code>.css.ts</code> file using TypeScript; a build step extracts them into a plain static <code>.css</code> file. No runtime style engine is sent to the client, and the result is fully compatible with Server Components.</p><div class=\"key\">Runtime CSS-in-JS injects styles during render — costing CPU, bundle size, and hydration complexity, and it can't run in React Server Components; the 2026 answer is zero-runtime/compile-time tooling that extracts static CSS at build, keeping colocation and typing while removing the render-path cost.</div>"},
  "reduced-motion": {"teach":"<p>At its core, <code>prefers-reduced-motion</code> is just <strong>a way to ask 'has this user told their operating system they don't want a lot of animation?' and adjust your styles accordingly</strong>. It's not a niche nicety — it reflects a real accessibility setting that some people depend on.</p><h4>Why it exists</h4><p>For users with vestibular disorders, large motion — sweeping parallax, big slide-and-zoom transitions, auto-scrolling carousels — can trigger genuine dizziness, nausea, or disorientation. Their OS exposes a 'reduce motion' toggle, and <code>@media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce)</code> lets your CSS respond to it.</p><div class=\"analogy\">Think of it like the lights-up cue in a theater for someone sensitive to strobe effects. You don't cancel the entire show — you swap the flashing strobe sequence for a gentle, steady fade so they can still follow the story safely. Reduced motion is the same: keep the meaning, drop the parts that make people sick.</div><h4>Reduce, don't obliterate</h4><p>The single most misunderstood point: the setting says <em>reduce</em>, not <em>eliminate</em>. Motion often carries meaning — a subtle transition tells you a panel opened, a fade tells you content changed. Blanket-killing every animation can strip away those essential cues and make the interface <em>more</em> confusing. The right move is to:</p><ul><li>replace big, traversal-heavy motion (parallax, slides, zooms) with subtle <strong>cross-fades</strong>,</li><li>stop autoplay and auto-scroll,</li><li>but keep small, informative transitions that aid comprehension.</li></ul><h4>The robust pattern: opt in to motion</h4><p>Rather than adding animation everywhere and then trying to switch it off, flip the default. Define your animations <em>only</em> inside <code>@media (prefers-reduced-motion: no-preference)</code>. That way the <strong>still, safe version is the baseline</strong>, and motion is the enhancement layered on for users who haven't asked to reduce it. If a browser or user setting is uncertain, they get the calm default — fail-safe by design.</p><h4>Why it matters</h4><p>Honoring this preference is a <strong>WCAG expectation</strong>, not an optional polish. Ignoring it can make your product literally unusable for affected users; over-applying it can break navigation cues for everyone. Getting the balance right is part of accessible engineering.</p><h4>Worked example</h4><p><code>@media (prefers-reduced-motion: no-preference) { .card { transition: transform .3s } }</code> — the card animates its transform <em>only</em> for users who have not requested reduced motion. Everyone else gets the instant, motion-free version as the default.</p><div class=\"key\">Wrap your motion in <code>@media (prefers-reduced-motion: no-preference)</code> so the still version is the safe default and animation is the opt-in enhancement — and remember the goal is to <em>reduce</em> harmful motion while keeping meaningful cues, which is a WCAG requirement, not a nicety.</div>"},
  "oklch": {"teach":"<p>At its core, <code>oklch()</code> is just <strong>a way to describe a color by how bright it looks, how colorful it is, and what hue it is — in a space engineered so that equal 'brightness' numbers actually look equally bright to your eyes</strong>. That last guarantee is what older color models fail to deliver.</p><h4>The three channels</h4><p><code>oklch(L C H)</code> breaks color into:</p><ul><li><strong>L — Lightness</strong>, perceptual brightness from 0 (black) to 100% (white).</li><li><strong>C — Chroma</strong>, how saturated/colorful it is (0 is gray; higher is more vivid).</li><li><strong>H — Hue</strong>, the angle on the color wheel (e.g. 250 is blue-ish).</li></ul><h4>Why 'perceptually uniform' is the whole point</h4><p>In <code>hsl()</code>, two colors with the same lightness number can look wildly different in actual brightness — <code>hsl</code> yellow at 50% lightness blazes far brighter than <code>hsl</code> blue at 50%. That makes generating consistent palettes a nightmare. In OKLCH, an <code>L</code> of 60% looks like roughly the same brightness whether the hue is yellow, blue, or red. So tints, shades, and contrast ramps behave predictably and stay legible.</p><div class=\"analogy\">HSL is like a thermostat whose '50' means a different actual temperature in every room of the house — set them all to 50 and some rooms freeze while others bake. OKLCH is a thermostat that's been carefully calibrated so '50' feels the same warmth everywhere. Now you can confidently set every room (every hue) to the same number and trust they'll feel consistent — which is exactly what you want when building a color system.</div><h4>Wide gamut: P3</h4><p>OKLCH also reaches beyond old sRGB. It can express vivid <strong>P3</strong> colors that hex and <code>hsl()</code> simply cannot represent — richer, more saturated greens and reds that modern displays can show. So your brand colors can be more vibrant on capable screens while degrading gracefully elsewhere.</p><h4>Programmatic theming</h4><p>Because the channels are independent and perceptual, you theme by nudging <em>one</em> channel. Want a hover state? Lower <code>L</code> by a few points and leave hue and chroma alone — you get a predictably darker shade of the <em>same</em> color, not a muddy hue shift. Pair it with <code>color-mix(in oklch, …)</code> to blend colors in this uniform space, and you have the foundation for generating entire token systems from a single seed color.</p><h4>The gotcha</h4><p>If you build a palette in HSL and assume equal lightness equals equal perceived brightness, your scale will look uneven — bright yellows leaping out, dark blues sinking back — and your contrast ratios won't be consistent. OKLCH is what fixes that.</p><h4>Worked example</h4><p><code>--brand: oklch(60% 0.15 250)</code> defines a blue, and <code>--brand-hover: oklch(55% 0.15 250)</code> is a cleanly darker version — only <code>L</code> dropped from 60% to 55%, with chroma and hue untouched, so it's unmistakably the same color, just slightly darker.</p><div class=\"key\">OKLCH describes color as perceptual Lightness, Chroma, and Hue in a uniform, wide-gamut (P3-capable) space — so equal L looks equally bright across hues, letting you build consistent palettes and theme programmatically by nudging a single channel, which HSL cannot reliably do.</div>"}
});
